[src:george-creamer/1884-in-baseball] Any team shown in small text indicates a previous team a player was on during the season.
[src:george-creamer/1884-in-baseball] Old Hoss Radbourn won a record 59 or 60 games (depending on the sources), a record that will almost certainly never be broken.
[src:george-creamer/1884-in-baseball] In addition to wins, Radbourn led the National League in games (75), games started (73), complete games (73), ERA (1.38), saves (2), strikeouts (441), and innings pitched (678.2).
[src:george-creamer/1884-in-baseball] The season record for pitching strikeouts (369, by Tim Keefe 1883) is broken by seven players, with Hugh Daily beating Keefe's record by 114.
[src:george-creamer/1884-in-baseball] To this day (as of 2020), six of the top ten strikeout seasons were accomplished in 1884 (including five of the top seven).
[src:george-creamer/1884-in-baseball] 1884 was the first season in which pitchers were allowed to throw overhand.
[src:george-creamer/al-buckenberger] Buckenberger was born in Detroit, Michigan, and began his career as an infielder, and then manager for minor league teams in the Midwest.
[src:george-creamer/al-buckenberger] In 1889 he became manager of the *Columbus Solons* of the American Association for two seasons.
[src:george-creamer/al-buckenberger] After a year at the minor league Sioux City, Iowa based Sioux City Cornhuskers he joined the National League *Pittsburgh Pirates* from 1892 to 1894, and then the *St.
[src:george-creamer/al-buckenberger] He managed the *Toronto Maple Leafs*, and the *Syracuse Stars* of the Eastern League for a year each, taking Syracuse to a first place finish in 1897.
[src:george-creamer/al-buckenberger] He then managed the Eastern League *Rochester Bronchos* from 1899 to 1901, finishing first-second-first.
[src:george-creamer/al-buckenberger] Following this he rejoined the National League as manager of the *Boston Beaneaters* from 1902 to 1904.
[src:george-creamer/al-buckenberger] He returned to Rochester between 1905 and 1908.
[src:george-creamer/al-buckenberger] Al Buckenberger also served as club president at Pittsburgh.
[src:george-creamer/al-buckenberger] His biggest successes were finishing second in the American Association in 1890 and finishing second in the National League at Pittsburgh in 1893.
[src:george-creamer/al-buckenberger] After his major league days he was part of a group, together with Francis Richter, editor of Sporting Life, and fellow manager Billy Barnie that tried and failed to resurrect the American Association.
[src:george-creamer/al-buckenberger] Buckenberger died at age 56 in Syracuse, New York.
[src:george-creamer/george-creamer] On August 20, 1883, after a game between the Louisville Eclipse and the Alleghenys‚ Creamer and fellow players Billy Taylor and Mike Mansell were each fined $100 and suspended indefinitely for drunkenness.
[src:george-creamer/george-creamer] In 1884, the Alleghenys finished with a 30–78–2 record and went through five managers.
[src:george-creamer/george-creamer] Creamer was the fourth of these managers, serving from August 6 to August 16 and losing all eight games he managed.
[src:george-creamer/george-creamer] Creamer was signed by the Baltimore Orioles before the 1885 season, but in March, newspaper reports said that he was very sick with tuberculosis and not expected to play baseball again.
[src:george-creamer/george-creamer] Players from the Chicago White Stockings took up a collection for Creamer and gave him $65.
[src:george-creamer/george-creamer] A benefit for him was scheduled for May 1 at the Academy of Music in Pittsburgh.
[src:george-creamer/george-creamer] A July 1885 newspaper article referred to a benefit that raised $200 for Creamer.
[src:george-creamer/george-creamer] In early May 1886, newspaper reports described Creamer as very ill in Waterbury, Connecticut.
[src:george-creamer/george-creamer] He died in Philadelphia, where he was interred at Greenwood Cemetery.
[src:george-creamer/george-creamer] Creamer was a member of the Knights of Pythias.
